@NODE Viewer
@TOC "Instructions/MAIN"
@TITLE "Viewer Program"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The @{" Electrics Viewer " LINK Picture_Database/Viewer.0/MAIN} program records Signals levels while the 
Simulator program is running a simulation.

  @{" Window      " LINK Window} - Layout of program window.
  @{" Signals     " LINK Signals} - List of Signals.
  @{" Trace       " LINK Trace} - Viewing simulation history.
  @{" Zoom        " LINK Zoom} - Changing the trace view zoom.
  @{" Marker      " LINK Marker} - Trace marker and values.
  @{" History     " LINK History} - Erasing simulation history.
  @{" ARexx       " LINK ARexx} - ARexx support.
  @{" Limitations " LINK Limitations} - Limitations, bugs, etc.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *      Viewer Window           *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Window
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Viewer Program Window"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Information Box @{fg text}@{bg background}
        
At the top of the @{" program window " LINK Picture_Database/Viewer.1/main} lies the Information Box.  This area
is used to indicate program status, and consists of the following 
three lines:

PROJECT: Project name.
TIME:    Visible time and Marker position.
MESSAGE: Error message or comment.

The TIME line indicates the first and last visible time, the time at
the Marker, and the difference between the current Marker time and
the previous Marker time.  For example:

  TIME: 0 to 55, 10 delta 5

  Beginning time = 0; End time = 55.
  Marker is on time 10, and was moved 5 time units.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Box @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Signal Box lies to the left of the program window.  This area
contains the list of Signals to have their history of activity
recorded. The activity of over 65000 Signals can be recorded at one
time.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Trace Box @{fg text}@{bg background}

The area below the Information Box and to the right of the Signal Box
is the Trace Box.  The record of a Signal's history is shown here as
a trace waveform.  Over 4.2 billion time units can be recorded and
viewed.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Viewer Signals        *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Signals
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Signals List"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal List @{fg text}@{bg background}

A Scroller at the right side of the Viewer window is used to adjust the
list of Signals in the Signal Box.  The center Slider part of the
Scroller represents the visible list of Signals, while any dark
crosshatched area represents Signals outside of view. The Signal list
view can be changed (if any part of the Signal list is not visible) by
moving the Slider part of the Scroller.

The keyboard Cursor keys (UP and DOWN) can also be used to change the
Signal list view.  The view will shift in the direction of the selected
Cursor key by about half of the current visible view.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Viewer Trace          *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Trace
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Trace Waveform"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The recorded history of a Signal is displayed in the Trace Box as a
trace waveform, and allows seeing the activity on one Signal with 
respect to others.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Waveform @{fg text}@{bg background}

A @{" trace waveform " LINK Picture_Database/Viewer.3/MAIN} may be for a single Signal, or a Signal Bus
containing many Signals.  The Signal level on a single Signal is
represented by the trace waveform as follows: 

    @{u}LEVEL              APPEARANCE          @{uu}
      0       Line along bottom of trace.
      1       Line along top of trace.
      X       Diagonal lines filling trace.
      Z       Line along center of trace.

A transition from one level to another would be shown as a vertical
line between the two levels.

The combined value of all individual Signals in a Signal Bus is
represented by the trace waveform as follows:

    @{u}    VALUE               APPEARANCE                  @{uu}
    All level "0"    Line along bottom of trace.
    All level "1"    Line along top of trace.
    All level "Z"    Line along center of trace.
    All level "X"    Line along top and bottom of trace.
    All different    Line along top and bottom of trace.

A transition from one value to another would be shown by two crossing
diagonal lines.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Trace Viewing @{fg text}@{bg background}

A Scroller below the Trace Box is used to adjust the view of the trace
history.  The center Slider part of the Scroller represents the visible
trace history, while any dark crosshatched area represents trace history
outside of view.  The view can be changed (if any part of the trace 
history is not visible) by moving the Slider part of the Scroller.

The keyboard Cursor keys (LEFT and RIGHT) can also be used to change the
trace history view.  The view will shift in the direction of the
selected Cursor key by about half of the current visible view.

The VIEW MARKER option in the VIEW menu can be used to change the
beginning time to that of the Marker time.

The BEGINNING option in the VIEW menu can be used to change the
beginning time.  A requester will appear, and a new time can be
entered.  If the time entered is greater than the total recorded time,
the beginning time will become the last recorded time.

The Information Box TIME line is updated when the beginning and
ending time the trace view is changed.  If there is less recorded
time than can be viewed, the end time will be that last recorded time.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Viewer Zoom           *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Zoom
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Viewer Zoom"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Trace View Zoom @{fg text}@{bg background}

The number of time units visible in the Trace Box can be changed by
zooming into or out from the trace waveform.  This is done by using
the ZOOM IN or ZOOM OUT options in the VIEW menu.  The beginning time
of the trace view will remain the same, while the end time changes.

The one other zoom control available is ZOOM FULL.  This option will
attempt to make all recorded Signal history visible in the Trace Box
by adjusting the zoom factor.  The beginning time is set to 0.  If all
recorded history cannot be fit, then only the first part will be
visible.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Viewer Marker         *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Marker
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Signal Trace Marker"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Trace Box has a @{" Marker " LINK Picture_Database/Viewer.4/MAIN} that can be placed on the trace waveform at
any time throughout the recorded trace history.  The Marker can indicate
Signal levels at that time, or measure the time between two events
on a waveform trace.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Moving the Marker @{fg text}@{bg background}

To position the Marker, click the left mouse button when the mouse
pointer is at a desired time in the Trace Box.  The Marker will then
move to that time.  The Marker time on the Information Box TIME line
will be updated, as well as the time difference between the old Marker
position and the new.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Marker Values @{fg text}@{bg background}

The levels present on the Signals at the Marker time are displayed at
the left edge of the Trace Box.  If a Signal value is too wide, it
will not be displayed.

To change the radix of a value, click on the Signal name next to the
value.  The selected Signal will be highlighted, and a @{" Radix Requester " LINK Picture_Database/Viewer.2/MAIN }
will appear.  Select a new radix, and press "Ok" to continue.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Viewer History        *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE History
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Viewer History"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Erasing all History @{fg text}@{bg background}

The recorded history of all Signals can be cleared by selecting the
ERASE ALL option in the HISTORY menu.  A requester will appear so the
operation can be confirmed.  Press "Yes" to continue, or "No" to cancel
the operation.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------------*
@REMARK * Viewer ARexx Support *
@REMARK *----------------------*
@NODE ARexx
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Viewer ARexx Support"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Viewer program supports an ARexx interface for selecting Signals
to have their activity recorded, and managing the recorded history.

  @{" Message Port " LINK Port} - ARexx message port.
  @{" Commands     " LINK Commands} - ARexx commands.
  @{" Error Codes  " LINK Errors} - ARexx error codes.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------------------*
@REMARK * Viewer ARexx Port *
@REMARK *-------------------*
@NODE Port
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Viewer ARexx Message Port"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Port @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each instance of the Viewer program will have a unique ARexx port
name, beginning with the program name, and ending with the instance
number (e.g. VIEWER.1, VIEWER.2, etc.).  The last line of the PROJECT
menu ABOUT requester shows the ARexx port name for the program.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-----------------------*
@REMARK * Viewer ARexx Commands *
@REMARK *-----------------------*
@NODE Commands
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Viewer ARexx Commands"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Commands @{fg text}@{bg background}

VIEW SIGNALLIST/A

  Provides a list of Signals to have their activity recorded.  Any
  existing Signals and their trace history will be erased.  A Signal
  name may appear any number of times in the list.  This command must
  be used before the Viewer program is connected to the Simulator,
  since the Signal names are required at that time.

  Examples: VIEW CLOCK
            VIEW RESET# CLK DATA[31:0]

RADIX SIGNAL/A,BIN/S,OCT/S,HEX/S

  Changes the radix of the Signal's value under the Marker to binary,
  octal, or hexadecimal.

  Example: RADIX DATA[3:0] HEX

BEGINNING TIME/N
  
  Changes the beginning time in the Trace Box.  If TIME is greater
  than the total recorded time, the last recorded time will be used
  instead.  If no time is given, time 0 will be used.

  Examples: BEGINNING
            BEGINNING 1000

ERASE

  Erases the recorded history of all Signals, and resets the recording
  time to 0.

END

  Changes the beginning time in the Trace Box to the last
  recorded time.

ZOOM IN/S,OUT/S,FULL/S

  Changes the trace waveform display zoom.  When zooming IN and OUT,
  the beginning time will remain the same.  A FULL zoom will try to
  make all recorded history visible in the Trace Box. 

  Example: ZOOM OUT

MARKER MARKERTIME/N,BEGINNING/S, END/S

  Moves the Trace Box Marker position.  The Information Box Marker
  times are changed, and the values of the trace waveform under the
  Marker are updated.  BEGINNING and END are an alternative to
  providing a time.  BEGINNING moves the Marker to time 0, and END
  moves the Marker to the last recorded time.  The trace waveform
  view is not changed to follow the Marker.

  Examples: MARKER 1000
            MARKER END

COLOR DARKTRACEBOX/S,LIGHTTRACEBOX/S

  Behaves the same as the DARK TRACEBOX option in the SETTINGS menu.
  The Trace Box colors are changed accordingly.  "COLOUR" will also be
  accepted as the command's spelling.

  Example: COLOR LIGHTTRACEBOX

GRID SHOW/S,HIDE/S

  Behaves the same as the SHOW GRID option in the SETTINGS menu.  The
  Trace Box grid is either visible, or not visible.

GETTOTALTIME

  Returns the total recorded time units.  The returned time will be
  between 0 and 4294967295.

NOP

  This command does nothing.  It could be used for locating a certain
  instance of the Viewer program by sending the command to see
  if it is accepted, or if an error occurs instead.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *---------------------*
@REMARK * Viewer ARexx Errors *
@REMARK *---------------------*
@NODE Errors
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Viewer ARexx Error Codes"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Error Codes @{fg text}@{bg background}

0  = No Errors.
11 = Syntax error in command.
12 = Unknown command.
13 = Unable to find requested Signal name.
20 = Out of memory.
@ENDNODE


@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *       Viewer Limitations     *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Limitations
@TOC Viewer
@TITLE "Viewer Program Limitations"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

This version of the Viewer program has several limitations that should
be noted.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Trace Zoom @{fg text}@{bg background}

There is a limit on how far out the trace waveform can be zoomed.
Therefore, the ZOOM FULL option will be unable to make all recorded
history visible in the Trace Box if the recorded history is very long.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Radix @{fg text}@{bg background}

The ARexx RADIX command will only change the radix of the first
instance of a Signal.  If the Signal appears more than once in the
Signal list, the others will remain unchanged.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Settings @{fg text}@{bg background}

The SETTINGS menu options cannot be saved.  They will be set to
default values when the Viewer program is started.
@ENDNODE
